Introduction

The following data set is a data set that focuses on tumor biopsy images. The data set contains the diagnosis of each image collected and also a series of measurements of the tumor scanned in the biopsy scan done. Its important for us to study the characteristics of a tumor, because it can help us hopefully identify if theres certain characteristics that make it more likely for a tumor to be malignant or benign. And hopefully through first looking at some of our variables through visualization to take a guess on some potentially clear determinants of benign vs.malignant and then through machine learning concepts create a model that through certain collection of measurements is able to pretty accurately identify a tumor as malignant or benign. This study is important because if we can create a model that identifies tumors with high accuracy, it not only would allow us to identify a greater amount of tumors, but also we could possibly expand healthcare access to lower income individuals as if a machine identifies the tumors, we could possibly lower the cost in the service meaning more people could afford it.

So what does this data set include? This data set focuses on collecting measurements of: 1. radius 2. texture 3. perimeter 4. area 5. smoothness 6.concavity 7. compactness 8. concave points 9. symmetry 10. fractal dimension And from these measurements variables containing the mean, standard error, and worst is calculated/found

However, lets mutate this so that the classification is either 1 for positive for a cancerous tumor or malignant or 0 for negative for a cancerous tumor or benign. Additionally, as there are 33 variables lets just look at the variables that focus specifically on averages of the different categories available. So this would be the variables: 1. diagnosis: Whether the tumor was diagnosed as malignant (1) or benign (0) 2. perimeter_mean: The average perimeter of cells in that particular biopsy 3. radius_mean: The average radius of cells in that particular biopsy 4. texture_mean: The average texture of cells in that particular biopsy 5. area_mean: The average area of cells in that particular biopsy 6. smoothness_mean: The average smoothness of cells in that particular biopsy 7. concavity_mean: The average concavity of cells in that particular biopsy 8. symmetry_mean: The average symmetry of cells in that particular biopsy

When thinking about malignant tumors, I would think that size has some influence to the tumor being benign or malignant. So lets start with looking at the relationship between radius mean and diagnosis.

So lets create a density plot to view the relationship between radius and diagnosis. I am choosing a density plot because it will give us a clear sense of how many times a tumor with a certain radius was categorized as benign or malignant and hopefully we will see a clear pattern.

The way we are going to do this is by assigning radius mean to the x variable in our ggplot. Then when we call our geom_density() function we want to be able to distinguish between malignant and benign so we will use our fill aesthetic to make the density graphs filled with two different colors for benign and malignant.

cancer %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = radius_mean)) + # assigning radius_mean to x variable
  geom_density(aes(fill = factor(diagnosis), alpha = 0.4)) + # adding in fill aesthetic to color code our two graphs
  geom_vline(xintercept = 18, color = "red") + # Adding this line in because I want to distinguish where the diagnoses seem to start changing to malignant
  labs(title = "Comparison between Tumor Diagnosis and Average Radius",
       x = "Average Radius",
       fill = "Diagnosis",
       alpha = "Color Intensity") # simply adding some labels

So there seems to be some of a positive correlation between average radius and diagnosis status where it seems that as the average radius increases, its more likely to be malignant. Where we can even just see with the vertical line I put in at about 18 radius, it becomes exclusively manignant.

So now that weve explored our variables a bit lets start creating some models. First though to recap from this exploration of data we can conclude that some features that seem to have some significance in diagnosis categorization are average radius, average symmetry, and average concavity.

Lets start with a very simple model. So because diagnosis is categorical it wouldnt actually make sense for us to explore a linear regression model as this is meant more for numerical values. Instead we are going to start with a decision tree as we can set the mode to classification instead of regression

To start with we need to split our data. We are also going to add a set.seed(9) so that we can replicate the data.

set.seed(9)
# 1 Splitting Data
cancer_split = initial_split(cancer, prop = 0.7) #Splitting data so that training dataset is 70% of our original dataset and testing dataset is 30% of our original dataset

cancer_train = training(cancer_split) # assigning training dataset to variable cancer_train
cancer_test = testing(cancer_split) # assigning testing dataset to variable cancer_test

So we have split our data into two datasets containing either 70% or 30% of our original dataset and assigned each to the variable ames_train or ames_test Next we are going to fit our model and as a reminder we are going to use a decision tree because we can set the mode to "classification. And the function for decision tree is decision_tree().

# Fitting the model 
cancer_tree = decision_tree() %>% # Choosing to keep all the defaults in our decision tree function 
  set_mode(mode = "classification") %>% # Need to set our mode manually to classification because our diagnosis variable is categorical 
  fit(factor(diagnosis) ~ radius_mean, data = cancer_train) # We are using our training data NOT our testing data. We need our testing dataset for assessing how accurate our model is in predicting diagnoses.

Note: We have to add the factor() function to the variable diagnosis because when we use a decision tree and set the mode to classification we made to make sure that the variable is classified as categorical.

Now that weve fitting our model lets create a prediction using our testing dataset

# Generate Predictions 
diagnosis_pred = cancer_tree %>%
  predict(new_data = cancer_test)

Random Forest

Why dont we try random forests next in improving our accuracy scores. A random forest model allows us to build a large collection of trees to improve our performance in making accurate predictions. It basically adds an extra layer of randomness to the model. We are basically creating at time hundreds of extra trees. Where at each split in the tree we choose a random subset of features to use. A random forest essentially is a more complex version of a bagged decision tree. Because I did not use a bagged decision tree in this data exploration so far, I want to go over what this type of model does and why its a foundational part of random forests. A bagged decision tree is based off a concept bootstrapping. What bootstrapping means is that its taking a dataset and creating dozens or hundreds of copies of it. So lets take our training set for example. Its taking this representation of data and then creating copies of this data but in different orders and always the same size sample.

So why dont we see if this type of model could improve our prediction accuracy. Lets split our data quickly and then fit our model once again this time using the function rand_forest().

set.seed(9) # Doing once again to replicate our results 
cancer_split = initial_split(cancer, prop = 0.7) #Splitting our dataset 70/30.

cancer_train = training(cancer_split) # Assigning slit datasets to our testing and training variables
cancer_test = testing(cancer_split)

fit_rf = rand_forest() %>%
  set_mode(mode = "classification") %>%
  fit(factor(diagnosis) ~ radius_mean + texture_mean + concavity_mean + symmetry_mean,
      data = cancer_train) # We are using our training data NOT our testing data. We need our testing dataset for assessing how accurate our model is in predicting diagnoses. We also need to make sure that our diagnosis variables is categorical so adding factor() in

Now lets generate once again our predictions using our testing dataset and see how well we did.

pred_rf = fit_rf %>%
  predict(new_data = cancer_test) # Here we are generating our predictions for our testing dataset

cancer_test %>%
  mutate(diagnosis_pred = pred_rf$.pred_class) %>% # mutating our testing dataset to include column of our predictions made

Weve improved our accuracy quite a bit through creating more complex models, but theres other factors that can make our models even more complex and adaptive. The last model that I would like to try before we go into hyperparameters and cross validation in order to help prevent overfitting is gradient boosting models.

This model is even more complex than a random forest because instead of creating an ensemble of deep independent trees the gradient bossting model is creating an ensemble of shallow trees and using the previous model learning from the model and improving upon it in the next model. So lets see how much this is going to improve our accuracy.

Weve already previously split our dataset so we are simply just going to fit the dataset to a new model using the function boost_fit() in order to implement our hopefully better performing model.

boost_fit = boost_tree() %>% #using boost_tree() function now to generate a gradient boost model fit with our training dataset
  set_mode(mode = "classification") %>% # setting our mode to classification
  fit(factor(diagnosis) ~ radius_mean + texture_mean + concavity_mean + symmetry_mean, data = cancer_train) # using `fit()` function to fit features to model

Now lets create some predictions using our testing dataset.

boost_pred = boost_fit %>%
  predict(new_data = cancer_test) # creating predictions using our testing dataset

cancer_test %>%
  mutate(diagnosis_pred = boost_pred$.pred_class) %>% # adding column in our cancer dataset of our predicted values
  accuracy(truth = factor(diagnosis), estimate = diagnosis_pred) #calculating accuracy score
## # A tibble: 1  3
##   .metric  .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>    <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 accuracy binary         0.930

So interestingly our accuracy actually goes down in comparison to the random forest, with a value of 92.98%. While, Im surprised by this, but it actually leads perfectly into what I wanted to focus on next. What I would like to know is if we adjust some of our hyperparameters, if our gradient boost model accuracy will go up.

When we are discussing GBM hyperparameters, there are really two specific categories we can focus on. So our two categories that we can focus on are: 1. Boosting hyperparemeters 2. Tree-specific hyperparameters

So what do these categories exactly mean? First off, I would like to first really clarify what hyperparameters means. Hyperparameters basically means that we are manually adjusting certain default features that are used in each of our models we use.

Lets focus now on what the categories of focus in gradient boost model hyperparameters mean.

First, when we are talking about specifically about boosting hyperparamers what we can adjust are: 1. Number of trees we use in the ensemble 2. Learn rate: which means we are adjusting how quickly our algorithm is learning from the previous trees (which personally, I am very interested in figuring out how this affects accuracy and also usually ranges from 0-1)

Second, when we are talking about tree-specific hyperparameters, we are talking about two areas to adjust: 1. Tree Depth: So controls the depth of our individual trees (usually 3-8) 2. Minimum observations in leaf nodes: Usually 5-15.

So instead of taking our default values of our boost_tree() function why dont we change the number of trees we use in the ensemble, the tree depth, and the learn rate. So the variables we are going to set ourselves specifically are: 1. trees: Lets try 550 here 2. tree_depth: Lets try 4 3. learn_rate: And here lets try 0.8 The thinking behind these values are that Im sort of trying to avoid the model possibly being overfitted so I dont want it to do too many trees or too much into depth, so going somewhere in between. In terms of the learn_rate, Im sort of thinking that if the learn rate is higher and it takes longer to learn from previous model maybe itll be more accurate Lets do this now.

boost_fit = boost_tree(trees = 550,
                       tree_depth = 4,
                       learn_rate = 0.8) %>% # setting my values here manually.
  set_mode(mode = "classification") %>% #setting mode to classification 
  fit(factor(diagnosis) ~ radius_mean + texture_mean + concavity_mean + symmetry_mean, data = cancer_train) # fitting our features to model

Now that we have fitting without any issues, lets generate some predictions

boost_pred = boost_fit %>%
  predict(new_data = cancer_test) # generating predictions using testing dataset not training dataset

cancer_test %>%
  mutate(diagnosis_pred = boost_pred$.pred_class) %>% #adding prediction column in our testing dataset
  accuracy(truth = factor(diagnosis), estimate = diagnosis_pred) # calculating accuracy score
## # A tibble: 1  3
##   .metric  .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>    <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 accuracy binary         0.924

So looks like us changing our hyperparameters from the default actually slightly worsened our accuracy where it lowered from 92.98% to 92.39%. This isnt a huge difference, but I would like to change my values slightly more as Im not entirely sure what to expect to see if I can improve. So lets do this next: 1. trees: Lets try 600 here 2. tree_depth: Lets try 5 3. learn_rate: And here lets try 0.8 I would like to leave this the same, just to keep something constant still

boost_fit = boost_tree(trees = 600,
                       tree_depth = 5,
                       learn_rate = 0.8) %>% # setting my values here manually.
  set_mode(mode = "classification") %>%
  fit(factor(diagnosis) ~ radius_mean + texture_mean + concavity_mean + symmetry_mean, data = cancer_train) #fitting features to model

Now lets generate some new predictions once again.

boost_pred = boost_fit %>%
  predict(new_data = cancer_test) #generating new predictions

cancer_test %>%
  mutate(diagnosis_pred = boost_pred$.pred_class) %>% #creating new column with predictions
  accuracy(truth = factor(diagnosis), estimate = diagnosis_pred) # calculating accuracy score

What I would like to try next is some cross validation.

So what is cross validation exactly. Cross validation is a resampling technique that randomly partitions out our training dataset into V smaller folds that are roughly the same size. This V value is usually 10 folds. And what it does is it trains ~90% of the training set and holds out ~10% of the dataset for assessment or testing how accurate our model is. And from there this is repeated for each fold. Then finally the estimates of these ten folds is averaged out. The reason that this concept is so valuable is because it helps avoid overfitting which is when the model has become so attuned to our dataset that the predictions become extremely accurate on our testing site but if we were to use model on new testing dataset the accuracy would be quite poor.

Now how do we a actually implement this idea? We will need to use several new functions to perform cross validation on our dataset. These functions are: 1. vfold_cv(data = ..., v = 10)": this will be used when we are data splitting 2. fit_resamples(): this is similar to our fitting steps 3. collect_metrics: automatically collects prediction metrics for each fold.

Lets put this into action now using our dataset. Note: We are going to use our cancer_train dataset to split into our standard 10 folds. And each fold will roughly be the same size.

cancer_folds = vfold_cv(cancer_train, v = 10) # using out training dataset we're creating ten folds (or splitting into roughly 10 parts)

Now lets fit our model again. We are also going to use random forest with our new variable cancer_folds. Especially as we seemed to have the best accuracy with our random forest model.

cancer_rf_rs = rand_forest() %>%
  set_mode(mode = "classification") %>%
  set_engine(engine = "ranger") %>% # Need to manually set this engine now with cross validations
  fit_resamples(factor(diagnosis) ~ radius_mean + texture_mean + concavity_mean + symmetry_mean, resamples = cancer_folds) # Need to use our `fit_resamples()` function for our cross validation not `fit()`

Lets see how our predictions did!

cancer_rf_rs %>%
  collect_metrics() #calculating our prediction averages
## # A tibble: 2  6
##   .metric  .estimator  mean     n std_err .config             
##   <chr>    <chr>      <dbl> <int>   <dbl> <chr>               
## 1 accuracy binary     0.925    10 0.00541 Preprocessor1_Model1
## 2 roc_auc  binary     0.972    10 0.00491 Preprocessor1_Model1

So our average accuracy is 91% which is pretty good and the second metric roc_auc is fairly good too. roc_auc is calculating the area under a roc curve which is a curve created from graphing on the x axis the false positive rate and on the y access true positive rate. The value would be between 0 and 1. AUC ranges in value from 0 to 1. A model whose predictions are 100% wrong has an AUC of 0.0; one whose predictions are 100% correct has an AUC of 1.0.. So because we have a value of 0.97 this is an extremely good average to have.

Overall I would say that our random forest model performs the best.

The last thing we can do in our exploration is tuning our hyperparameters in our decision tree model.

We can explore this through the tune() function from the tune package. This function allows us to put a placeholder for each of the hyperparameters in a decision tree. This allows the model to train several models on resampled training data (which we get through cross validation) to see which models are the best and basically tells us which hyperparameters perform the best without us manually adjusting everything like we did with the gradient boost model.

First we need to tune our hyperparameters. The two hyperparameters in decision trees are: 1. cost_complexity: which adds a penalty to error rates of more complex trees 2. tree_depth: as the name suggest, controls the depth of the tree (how many levels of splits the tree contains)

tree_tune_spec = decision_tree(
  cost_complexity = tune(), 
  tree_depth = tune()
) %>% # So what have we done here? Instead of leaving our default values like we usually do when calling our decision tree function we are putting `tune()` as our placeholder of what each hyperparameter value could be. Next we need to set our modes and engine
  set_mode(mode = "classification") %>% # As a reminder need to set to classification because our diagnosis is categorical
  set_engine(engine = "rpart")

Great lets set our tuning grid now. We are going to create a grid of possible candidate values for each hyperparameters. Lets keep it sort of simple where we will only create five levels because this will give us 36 possible hyperparameter combinations (6*6) which seems pretty expansive for this exploration.

tree_grid = grid_regular(cost_complexity(),
                         tree_depth(),
                         levels = 6) #creating our grid of possible hyperparameter combos

Now lets tune our model.

tree_tune_fit = tree_tune_spec %>%
  tune_grid(factor(diagnosis) ~ radius_mean + texture_mean + concavity_mean + symmetry_mean, 
            resamples = cancer_folds,
            grid = tree_grid
        ) # We need our cross validations dataset and we also need to add in our grid so that it runs through all our possible hyperparameters

Lets see what is our best hyperparameter through once again collect_metrics(). For this purpose lets filter twice. One variable will be accuracy and the other roc_auc.

tree_tune_fit %>%
  collect_metrics() %>% #getting our predictions

Conclusion

So throughout this data exploration it looks like our random forest model was the best model to do with an accuracy of about ~94.2%. And this model also held out fairly well to our cross validation test as even with this attempt to check how the model would compare if we used potentially other similar data we had an accuracy score of 91%.

I would like to add as well that we likely had already such good accuracy results due to us seeing in our data exploration already very good indicators of features determining if tumor malignant or benign.

In the future if we wanted to know if there were any other features that had clear distinctions to add to our model to possibly get even more of an accurate prediction model for classifying tumors as benign or malignant, we would start again by doing some visualizations to determine what has strong distinctions and then add it to our models.
